Republican strategy to counter Obama’s reelection
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of election fraud in the U.S. in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for holding federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws since 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon increased after the November 2010 elections, which added 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 States were introduced in the only year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identity card and proof of American citizenship.
Furthermore, these laws also reduce voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the vote, and withdraw citizens with a judicial record their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo identity card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities urged to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo identity card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people in the age of voting, have no photo identity cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Furthermore, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a ID.
It often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required ID card with photography.
A lot more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their ID card with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states authorize members of the fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws demanding voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
There are two out of three Spanish voters that promote the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican legislators sponsored laws abolishing voters on the day of voting in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of people and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to recording about 10 million citizens.
However, measures taken since 2009 have dropped the registration rate of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
Furthermore, Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while they represented only 13% of state voters.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who formed 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetos of the Democratic Governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to reduce the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have adopted laws requesting the presentation of a photo identity card.
Nevertheless, the new rules implemented will undoubtedly make the exercise of voting rights more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the supporting nature of the laws that have been voted and they see an obvious goal of influencing the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Centre demonstrates that the States that adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes necessary for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to make sure that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
