Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of the European Space Agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern block (the Czech Republic became fully member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of projects from the agency over the years following.
The road from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.
Before the Second World War, passionate Polish worked on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6, 1933, during which he presented ideas from his leading work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics " .
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his book "Introduction to astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) became subsequently a large propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many works devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was particularly rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden face of the Moon.
As of 1925, a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should be used to drive or brake the draisin.
The only information known on this drain is that of the press of the time.
As of 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It is evident from the retained documents that this research had reached the trial stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, drawn by engineer Rohziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by a author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of the rocket technique were conducted by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the works.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is concerned in the November 1954 issue journal, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the area of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautic Federation (created in 1951) and as early as the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice President of the International Astronautic Federation.
He retained his function until his death in 1959.
As of 1956, the PTA provided a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight trials were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and serve to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket was developed during the period 1962 - 1965, following the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of engines was 37 km.
In the 1965-1968 period, Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the Aeronautics Institute, the first flight trials began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
It is also important to mention the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
