The Argo movie: When everything goes to the most bad, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamist students took assault on the U.S. Embassy of Tehran and retained 52 diplomats in hostages.
They had to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, give up Shah because it would have shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the liberation of the hostages.
It was a hard shot for the U.S. prestigious, still worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The abducted diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations held by the Algerian government.
Their fate raises a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iran feeling in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter’s defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated peripheries, they met in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to leave them out of Iran through a rocky cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team coming to make tracks for the shooting of a large science fiction show.
Combination of Genres
The exfiltration expert Tony Mendez’s plan requires Hollywood’s collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized shops reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained long secret, the film was based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck movie is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - such as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
Atmospheres succeed: Tehran sequences of documentary style (in subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been retranscrited in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions with common men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his play of actor stopped raising ironic remarks.
Argo is his third film after the dark police officer "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It’s also the first Affleck film that doesn’t take place in his original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictibility when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his employees get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazar).
Too many shares in too many places
The director had to be satisfied with a topic that actually offers few palpitable scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
It goes very well, sometimes it adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is displaced by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track is pushed pretty much by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissolved character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far away, the only ones in this case.
Affleck’s movie lacks a little dramatic tension, it is left to be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the achievement and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story again, in some way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services such as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the case.
