The architects of the MVRDV cabinet prove that the real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountain - 2 photos
“I think this building is funny, it is very futuristic, finally something interesting to see,” Lisette Verhaig, a crossing on the bottom of the street, says.
Stefan Spermon, an informatician in a large neighboring company, says, “Yes, he’s really beautiful, this building.”
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, nobody goes in one of these ringing libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dorm town that has nothing attractive to the gates of Rotterdam, holds a quite special record.
The 80,000-soul municipality shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to regain some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in armed concrete painted.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city's authorities realized that there was only one way to resume the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam MVRDV architect office, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of buildings full of mind and often cynics, accepted the project with his usual flegma and presented himself at the competition in 2003 with five pounds under the arm and richness on the face.
And while the members of the jury still looked at each other, disappointed and haunted the shoulders, Maas, the faced, stacked his choice books by order of size to make it a pyramid, and finished his speech with activist arguments: "Common cherry!"
Here is my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as it is said, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain sprang out of land.
The building is part of a revitalization project including a underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few mitoyen buildings and houses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the book mountain received the second award "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This little tender village, which until today had nothing to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and a town hall of a disgusting, white facades invite to think that it is home to milk, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long path to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under the bell of cheese.
Certainly, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massive, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you crawl the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and light, the floor in Dutch bricks and elegant reverberies speak clearly the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public banks, dogs and little boys and girls playing the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more.
“Normally, the library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and unpersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We have completely disturbed the classic space configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the book mountain was rightly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical plant of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambs, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hard building architects and engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, for years, the synthetic membrane of a millimeter thick has been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we save time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, in plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 stairs is the top of the mountain.
After nearly 500 metres, the literary cafe offers us a stunning view of the city, as well as Dutch croquets and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but mostly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of moisture in the literary mountain air.
Donations to the new soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all glass surfaces, this building is a model ecology project,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is set by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun lights only a short time inside, even in the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wood beams mounted backwards compared to the glass facade serve as sunshine, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very nice.
Completely automated stores load the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic computerman mentioned above, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there too.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "the finally found soul".
In fact, a few weeks ago, during the opening, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has filled the empty of the library that was not yet completely filled (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, “there is nothing worse than a library half empty.”
“I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even though it’s only for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline called, in the professional jargon, the creation of an identity.
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even though it may seem young and little educated.
This is finally a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany has chosen abstention during the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against Palestinians’ request to obtain the status of observer state to the United Nations.
But then she chose the abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not agree to what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, because it has special relationships with Israel.
But I also think it doesn’t support the US position either.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, however, without being too critical to Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen abstention during the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy that is defined by the Americans and establishing a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
Therefore, the Germans face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still tasting to find this role, but are on the path towards a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What does then concretely mean the term "normal" foreign policy for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent from those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other major powers: this is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany’s position towards the Middle East conflict and abstention during the United Nations vote?
Germany first has significant results in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to strike the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a crucial element.
However, I wouldn't give too much importance to this, because it's not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a crucial element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany disrupt its relationships with the United States by choosing abstention on important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans understand perfectly the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will only be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced their veto with a clear voice.
Does opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the US internal political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government of course cannot defend its position publicly.
I think the real differences in opinions are not so big that they always seem.
If you observe the relationships between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiasm over Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany experience difficulty in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other hand?
I think it doesn’t make things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for Germans if there was a consistent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore register within a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing in the issue of the euro.
In my view, Germany will take a locomotive role in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not simple for Germany, especially because of the relationships with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But I believe that the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that marks more their independence.
Does Germany seem to play a role as a weight player on the international stage, does Germany only want to take a key role?
Does it always have difficulties in taking leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still having difficulty playing a more important role.
If, for example, we look at the euro crisis, we note that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn’t make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must compose with neighbors and very varied opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the U.S. influence on European policy only decreases, but at the moment the EU does not fill this empty, then who remains?
Germans simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Washington Transatlantic Academy, an institute in which academics and policy experts in Europe and North America together analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German policy, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Became Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are brands known worldwide.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is hidden a trademark officially registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
The brand therefore has a protection such as that the company bearing its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not sure she would gain a cause.
“It’s increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” explains Thomas Pattloch, Taylor Wessing’s lawyer specializing in violation of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
Imitators need only a few additional letters to be able to record their brands.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also copied legally, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports items.
Pattloch opens a booklet in which the recordings made from the Beijing brand office are located.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by appropriating a portion of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copy and violation of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping centers that sell virtually only counterfeiters.
The cases of Pattloch, however, are different: its commissioners charge him to address the fact that the Chinese brand office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name already protected in another country.
The Chinese talk about "Bang Mingpai", a relative brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women are designated to marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame themselves.
“It’s bad for business, we need to fight this trend,” Pattloch says.
“The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous.”
Financial losses and judicial costs are millions for the sectors concerned, especially in terms of expensive lighthouse products.
According to data from the CLSA market analysis company, China represents, with an annual volume of EUR 15 billion, the third world market for luxury products and the fastest growing market.
However, it is not easy to radiate the doubtful records from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reported the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long time, the criticized name had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarism, because he would have hurt his brand in China.
In this field, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also relate to graphic elements.
