“This has allowed people to have a broader range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and the establishment of a family,” she explains.
These changes in social standards contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and birth, resulting in a decreased birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the decrease of population has created resentment within the local population.
In Singapore there are websites that abundantly disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially against Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating themselves.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore has experienced its worst electoral results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to fix the problem with the establishment of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenue, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities began controlling the number of small apartments, known as "shoe box", which can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale gains a lot of success.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” are sold much faster than larger housings.
