For this reason, it is much more cost-effective for our cash.
However, he acknowledges that the new standards give clearer instructions to the promoters, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too much small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new regulations could be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, discussing with the Singaporeans working in the central financial district, it would seem that they are not going to have a lot of effects.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive, just like education, that’s why people give it back to later,” a young framework said.
Other people may have children.
“But for me it’s important to have my money and time,” another 20-year-old young man says.
Men and women mention their career, stress and cost of access to property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
Thus, although the government tries to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
