The UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration to be made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, although it was announced previously and theoretically adopted by the seven present representatives.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of States and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency reported initially that it would be released after the summit closed, and then stated that it would be published from one moment to another on the website of the government.
When they were asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exhibited by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private, restricted audio session" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated between journalists was given by the press officers of some of the UNASUR governments who attended the appointment, except for the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released on the day was the list of presidents present, causing some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media that claimed more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd Summit of South America Arab Country (ASPA) and, although this was requested by the press, he did not also share the statement called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, you can verify that the document was published last March.
During both international appointments, Peruvian authorities have tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited to the maximum obtaining of information.
The summit was also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment by the Hague Court that separates a different border between the two countries.
Peru’s Presidents Ollanta Humala and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial that Lima attempted against Santiago and which begins Monday in the Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will solve the disputes we have today in front of this international court," President Humala said in a statement.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international courts," President Piñera added by giving a handful to President Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Covenant by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of the international court, following a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered as seriously wrong.
The summit held without the presence of Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the UNASUR since 2011 after the destitution of its former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closeing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The official read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines of 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would put into place "important steps to achieve the purpose of South American citizenship through the development of residence permit agreements."
He informed that actions would be implemented to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better drug accessibility, low-cost internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a crisis-in-Europe, “economic consolidation (Latin America) should not have a triumph matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and entertain a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by joining our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were concerned with Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although it had not given more details.
Similarly, the final document refers to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the South American Nations Union," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbors, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional appointment, he hoped to meet his Nicaragua counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a judgment by the CIJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We're going to review all these pathways, they're not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for discussion with this country," he said.
“I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible,” said President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday where they planned to attend the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, to take power.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the block Defence Ministers will meet beforehand to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which attempts to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are part of the Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru provides the pro temporal presidency of the regional block.
