A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he was launching there an irresistible hameson: the end of the “big count” of the Maya calendar on December 21, to which many people refer as the proof of the end of the coming world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax hunger some called "the Armageddon of Debt" and an increasing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end of time thought it was triggering the apocalypse.
“I didn’t realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker dispenses the course "Medias, Culture and End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetic scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could burst.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
